Exploratory Data Analysis of Dating Platform: Veggie Mingle

Bret Wilde-Webster

17 February 2025

1. Introduction

Veggie Mingle is a dating platform for vegetarians, vegans, and other plant-based diet enthusiasts in the US. Individuals who share these diets often share common beliefs, mindsets, and lifestyles. Hence, the thinking goes, they might be interested in finding like-minded partners who share their same ethical, environmental, and health perspectives.

The challenge that Veggie Mingle faces, despite a dedicated user base and a very clear niche, is that match rates (whether or not any given individual does or does not find a match in a given time period) continue to remain low. The goal of this report is to conduct exploratory data analysis and develop machine learning models in order to identify which factors contribute to a successful match.

If users, no matter how much they may enjoy the platform, do not see successful results- they may begin to leave the platform. Understanding how and why people either do or do not match is crucial to the future success of Veggie Mingle.

1.1 Study and Data Summary

The data consists of 5000 records, split across 35 variables. 70% of the data is qualitative, representing lifestyle choices or demographic information. The remaining 30% is quantitative, representing more granular information, such as age, online activity, and profile completeness. Refer to Tables 2.0.1 and 2.0.2 for an overview of the data types and match outcomes.

The guiding question of this report is, “What user attributes contribute most significantly to a successful match on Veggie Mingle?”

The report seeks to answer this through evaluating six specific variables. Those factors are: favorite activity (1), alcohol consumption levels (2), income levels (3), travel preferences (4), music preferences (5), and how often one was active on the dating app (measured as “Online Activity” (6)).

Afterwards, we will present our most key considerations from the analysis. This includes revisiting the findings deemed most important, additional insights only available once the initial findings are available, and new questions for future analysis. Finally, we will put forward our actionable recommendations based on those conclusions.

1.2 Preliminary Conclusions:

  1. There are two outcome variables, the most important one being “Matched,” with levels “Yes” or “No.” The second is “Total Matches” which is a numeric variable that measures the total matches for each user. Both metrics are measured within the first 30 days of a user joining Veggie Mingle.

    1. The median total matches is five, with a standard deviation of two. This means that if a user does successfully match, even once, on average, they will match four more times. Refer to Table 2.0.3 to see basic summary statistics on total matches.

    2. This means that the value of matching the very first time is disproportionately more effective and important in determining total matches than any other variable.

  2. Relationships between Matched and other variables, if they exist, have very small effects on matching outcomes. Machine Learning models, as a result, struggled to accurately predict correct outcomes.

2. Exploratory Data Analysis

These factors were chosen specifically because they represent variability in lifestyle choices, which, given that the premise of Veggie Mingle is predicated upon similar lifestyle and diet choices- seem like an apt place to find important differences in match outcomes. The data set is skewed, with only 35% of users receiving at least one match.

The hypothesis in selecting these specific variables, is that there is a relationship between self-identified lifestyle preferences and matching.

2.1 Activity Preferences

Is there a relationship between activity preferences and receiving a match?

Data

“Favorite Activity” is a categorical variable consisting of four levels, Hiking, Yoga, Music, and Reading. Users identify which activity is their favorite among these four. This variable was combined with “Matched” to see if any activities had higher shares of matches than any other activities.

Method

Frequency distributions were computed to evaluate the two variables for a relationship. To visualize that distribution, a stacked bar chart was created displaying the ratio of favorite activities by match outcome.

Analysis

Table 2.1.1 shows that all activity preferences have very similar ratios of “Yes” to “No” for matching. Yoga has the highest proportion of successes. Figure_2.1.1, a stacked bar plot, shows that any difference in proportions is exceedingly small.

Results

There is not enough evidence to conclude that a relationship exists between favorite activity and receiving a match. At first glance, it might seem that there are significant differences in the number of matches for each activity. However, this difference is due to the unequal distribution of total selections—more people enjoy hiking than reading, for example. When we look at the proportion of each activity’s selections that result in a match, the differences become less significant. See Figure 2.1.1 for more details.

2.2 Alcohol Consumption

Is there a relationship between alcohol consumption and receiving a match?

Data

“alcohol_consumption” is a categorical variable consisting of three levels, Never, Regularly, and Socially. Users identify which type of alcohol consumption matches their own among these three. This variable was combined with “Matched” to see if any level of alcohol consumption had higher shares of matches than any other activities.

Method

Two frequency distributions were computed to evaluate the two variables for a relationship. The first created a cross tabulation of alcohol consumption levels on the entire data set, Table 2.2.1. The second shows the ratio of match outcomes by alcohol consumption levels, 2.2.2.

Analysis

Table 2.2.1 shows an extremely unequal distribution of alcohol consumption levels, with social drinkers accounting for just above 50% of all users. “Never” accounts for 39.5%, and “Regularly” accounts for 10%.

Table 2.2.2 shows a small range of differences among “Yes” match outcomes. Social drinkers are 5.2% more likely to receive a match than regular drinkers, and 2% more likely than those who never drink.

Results

The differences between the ratios within each category are small and might seem insignificant on their own. However, since social drinkers make up half of all users and are the most likely to receive a match compared to other alcohol consumption categories, they have a significant advantage. Half of the time a user is on Veggie Mingle, they will either be viewing the profile of a social drinker or be a social drinker themselves.

This overlap in interests, combined with the slightly higher odds of success for social drinkers, provides enough evidence to suggest a potential relationship between alcohol consumption and receiving a match.

2.3 Income Levels

Is there a relationship between income level and receiving a match?

Data

“income_level” is a categorical variable consisting of three levels, High, Middle, and Low. Users identify which income level matches their own among these three. This variable was combined with “Matched” to see if any income level contributes more to a successful match than any other level of income.

Method

Two frequency distributions and a summary table were computed to evaluate the two variables for a relationship. The first created a cross tabulation of income levels on the entire data set, Table 2.3.1. The second shows the ratio of match outcomes by income levels, Table 2.3.2.

Finally, Table 2.3.3 shows the average total matches across income levels.

Analysis

Observing Table 2.3.2, it would appear that proportionally, high income respondents see a minimal increase in match likelihood. High income minglers can expect to be matched 3.7% more than those identifying as “middle” income, and 1.4% more than “low” income.

Observing Table 2.3.1, high income users represent the smallest section of respondents, and there are far more total matches in “middle” income.

Looking at table 2.3.3, when isolating for just those respondents who had were matched; there is nearly no difference in average total matches between income levels.

Results

Despite representing almost half of the data set, users of middle income are the least likely to receive a match. High income users are more likely than any other group to receive a match, despite representing the smallest share of users. However, that increased likelihood is very slight. None the less, a difference does exist, and could imply a relationship between income levels and match likelihood.

2.4 Travel Preferences

Is there a relationship between travel preferences and receiving a match?

Data

“travel_preference” is a categorical variable consisting of four levels, Adventurous, Cultural, “Rarely Travel”, and Relaxing. Users identify which travel type they enjoy most among these four. This variable was combined with “Matched” to see if any travel preference contributes more to a successful match than any other.

Method

A summary table was created to evaluate the two variables for a relationship. Table 2.4.1. shows the ratio of successful matches by travel preferences, “MatchRatio”, the total count of users who prefer each travel type, “SelectionCount”, and the proportion of total users who selected each travel type, “SelectionRatio”.

Analysis

Table 2.4.1 shows that 37% of users who prefer adventurous travel received matches—3.5% higher than cultural travelers, 3.1% higher than those who rarely travel, and 2.6% higher than those who prefer relaxing vacations. Interestingly, only 10% of users reported rarely traveling, suggesting that Veggie Mingle attracts users who enjoy some form of travel. This is consistent with the platform’s focus on shared lifestyle traits.

Results

The proportion of successful matches for travel preferences other than Adventurous is within 1%, while Adventurous stands apart with a higher match rate. This suggests a potential relationship between travel preferences and match likelihood. Additionally, given that 90% of users enjoy some form of travel, users who also enjoy traveling are more likely to share a lifestyle in common with others, increasing their chances of a match.

2.5 Music Preferences

Is there a relationship between music preferences and receiving a match?

Data

“music_taste” is a categorical variable consisting of four levels, Classical, Jazz, Pop, and Rock. Users identify which type of music they enjoy most among these four. This variable was combined with “Matched” to see if any type of music taste contributes more to a successful match than any other.

Method

Two frequency distributions and a heat map were created to evaluate the two variables for a relationship.

The first frequency distribution shows the ratio of match outcomes by music taste, Table 2.5.1. The second shows a cross tabulation of music tastes across the entire data set, Table 2.5.2.

Finally, Figure 2.5.1 shows the shift in match likelihood by music taste, using a heatmap. A lighter green represents a higher number, and a darker shade of green represents a lower number.

Analysis

Looking to Table 2.5.1., nearly 70% of all users who enjoy pop music were unsuccessful in receiving a match, as opposed to those who enjoy classical music, of which 42% were successful in receiving a match

Users who enjoy classical music are 11.9% more likely to receive a match than those who enjoy pop music, 7.6% more likely than those who enjoy jazz, and 7.4% more likely than those who enjoy rock.

Referring to Table 2.5.2., more users prefer pop music than any other kind of music, while jazz has the lowest share of users. Rock and classical music are roughly tied.

Observing Figure 2.5.2., differences in match likelihood become much more clear. The panel for pop music is nearly white, showing the high number of users with a taste for pop music who did not receive a match.

Results

There is a clear and obvious preference among users for individuals with a taste for classical music. Users who identify classical music as their favorite see large and noticeable increase in positive match outcomes. Conversely, those with a taste for pop music are overwhelmingly unlikely to receive a match.

Referring again to the heat map, there is definitively enough evidence to conclude that a relationship exists between music taste and match likelihood.

2.6 Online Activity

Is there a relationship between different levels of online activity and receiving a match?

Data

“online_activity” is a numeric variable consisting of a scale from 1-10. It measures the hours the user spends online daily. This variable was combined with “Matched” to see if any type of music taste contributes more to a successful match than any other.

Method

Two frequency distributions and a violin plot were created to evaluate the two variables for a relationship.

The first frequency distribution shows the ratio of match outcomes by level of online activity, Table 2.6.1. The second shows a cross tabulation of online activity levels across the entire data set, Table 2.6.2.

Figure 2.6.1 shows the distribution of matches across “Yes” and “No” match outcomes across online activity.

Analysis

Looking at Table 2.6.1., the proportion of “Yes” responses across activity levels one through five remains steady, between 31% and 35%. However, at activity levels six and beyond, the likelihood of receiving a match increases significantly, with 38% to 42% of users at these levels receiving a match.

Table 2.6.2. shows that the data is skewed, with 74.9% of users falling within activity levels 1 to 5. Despite this skewness, the increased match likelihood at higher activity levels (6 and beyond) cannot be attributed to the distribution of users. Since the majority of users are concentrated at lower activity levels, the higher match likelihood at activity levels 6 and beyond is not simply a byproduct of skewness.

Figure 2.6.1., the violin plot, further illustrates this, with clear peaks observed between online activity levels 3 and 5. While the “No” plot shows sharper peaks, Table 2.6.3. reveals that both matched and unmatched individuals share the same average level of online activity.

Results

Based on the analysis, there is enough evidence to establish a relationship between higher online activity and positive match outcomes. While the distribution of online activity is skewed with the majority of users concentrated at lower activity levels, the significant increase in match likelihood at activity levels 6 and above indicates that users with higher online activity are more likely to receive a match.

3.0 Linear Regression

Model Performance

R-squared measures how well the model explains how much of the change in the outcome variable (total matches) is explained by the change in the variables within the linear regression model. It ranges from 0 to 1, where 1 means the model perfectly predicts the outcomes, and 0 means it predicts nothing better than guessing the average.

Here, this models R² value is 0.02375 or 2.4%, meaning that only 2.4% of the change in our outcome is explained by the change in our model. Most of the variation in total matches remains unexplained.

RMSE measures the average difference between the model’s predictions and the actual data. Smaller values indicate a better fit. In this case, the model’s RMSE is 2.772. So, on average, the model’s predictions for total matches are off by about 2.77 matches. Given the smaller scale, this is a relatively large margin of error.

One other important statistic here is the P-Value. The P-Value here is 0.03587, where the threshold for labeling a model as statistically significant is a value less than 0.05. We can see that the model is just barely under that, which, combined with the poor RMSE and R² value, communicates that the model does not accurately predict total matches.

3.1 Logistic Regression

Logistic Regression performs poorly. With an AUC ROC score of 0.5346 (Table 3.1.1), the model is only marginally improved over random guessing. There is a common convention of assigning AUCROC scores letter grades to evaluate the model’s performance, which, in this case, is an F. Referring to the ROC curve, we can see that it is nearly flat (Figure 3.1.1)

The F1 measure (Table 3.1.3) of this model is 0.1588, which is very poor. This tells us that the model cannot effectively tell the difference between a true negative/positive and a false negative/positive.

By way of explanation, we can observe the confusion matrix (Table 3.1.2). The confusion matrix reveals that the model misidentifies the vast majority of true positive values as false, and the vast majority of true negative values as positive.

In other words, the model is easily confused. It cannot tell the difference between what should really be a match (incorrectly predicting no match) and what should not result in a match (incorrectly predicting a match).

3.2 Quadratic Discriminant Analysis

The Quadratic Discriminant Analysis model performs poorly, albeit better than the logistic regression model. With an AUC ROC score of 0.5432 (Table 3.2.1), the model is only a marginal improvement over random guessing. There is a common convention of assigning AUCROC scores letter grades to evaluate the model’s performance, which, in this case, is an F. Referring to the ROC curve, we can see that it is nearly flat (Figure 3.2.1), this is an indication that the model likely is not learning anything useful, or is struggling to find trends.

The F1 measure (Table 3.2.3) of this model is 0.2077. This is the best F1 score of any of the three classification models attempted, but it is still not an acceptable score. The score tells us that the model cannot effectively tell the difference between a true negative/positive and a false negative/positive.

By way of explanation, we can observe the confusion matrix (Table 3.2.2). The confusion matrix reveals that the model misidentifies the vast majority of true positive values as false, and the vast majority of true negative values as positive.

In other words, the model is easily confused. It cannot tell the difference between what should really be a match (incorrectly predicting no match) and what should not result in a match (incorrectly predicting a match).

3.3 Random Forest (Best Model)

Model Performance

A random forest model consists of many different decision trees, which are like flowcharts used to determine what variables have the largest effect on the outcome. Each tree is trained on a different subset of data, and their answers are combined through a majority vote. This helps make the decision more accurate and reliable by considering different viewpoints and avoiding overfitting to any one set of details.

The Random Forest model is the best model so far, and an improvement over previous models, but still performs poorly. With an AUC ROC score of 0.5828 (Table 3.3.1), the model is an improvement over random guessing, but not by much. There is a common convention of assigning AUCROC scores letter grades to evaluate the model’s performance, which, in this case, despite the improvements, it is still an F. Referring to the ROC curve, we can see that it is nearly flat (Figure 3.3.1)

The F1 Score (Table 3.3.3) shows the combined value of how well the model accounts for false negatives, and false positives, simultaneously. The F1 measure of this model is, 0.1588, which is very poor. The model, like the others, cannot effectively tell the difference between a true negative/positive and a false negative/positive.

By way of explanation, we can observe the confusion matrix (Table 3.3.2). The confusion matrix reveals that the model misidentifies the vast majority of true positive values as false, but correctly identifies nearly all true negatives!

In other words, essentially, the model is shy. It is extremely cautious of predicting positive values, and over assigns its guesses to the “No” for predicted match values. Actually, almost all of its predictions were of the “No” value, which accounts for why it labeled all the true negatives correctly. This is likely due to the skewed nature of the data set, where more than 65% of the users did not get a match.

Model and Variable Importance Explanation

Looking towards Figure 3.3.1., there are several surprises. First, disregard User_id, as that is simply an identifier for each unique user of Veggie Mingle. The first thing I notice here is that of the variables selected in the initial exploratory data analysis, only two are present here. Those being music taste, in the form of Jazz, and in online activity. They are weighted heavily in the importance plot, showing that they have out sized power in determining match outcomes.

The top three variables according to the plot are profile completeness, age, and account duration.

Expected error on the model for future data

The model has extraordinarily high accuracy on negative values only. This indicates that if the model can be convinced to take more positive guesses, it may be far more accurate than it currently appears. But, until that modification is made, I would not recommend this model for deployment. It is currently exceedingly inaccurate, and given that it did not test well, it likely will not fare well on future data either.

4. Recommendations

1.) App Engagement

The exploratory data analysis shows that increased online activity is directly correlated with match likelihood (Table 2.6.1). The random forest variable importance plot (Figure 3.3.1) highly ranks profile completeness and account duraction as predictors for match success.

There should be a renewed focus on keeping Veggie Mingle users engaged and active on the app. This could be accomplished through more active users being shown more often to more active users, or disincentive incomplete profiles in the suggested profiles algorithm. There could also be incentives provided. If Veggie Mingle has paid “super likes” or other such resources normally paid for, perhaps upon a user fully completing their profile, they might receive one such paid resource for free.

Users are more likely to be satisfied on Veggie Mingle if, being an active user, they match with another active user. This could lead to more immediate conversations or faster outcomes. There is also the inherent assumption that a more active user is a more invested user, and therefore, when seeing another profile which has a higher online activity- is seeing another user more invested in successful matches.

2.) Emphasize Shared Lifestyle Traits

Repeatedly, in the exploratory data analysis and in the VIP plots for linear regression (Figure 3.0.2) and random forest (Figure 3.3.1), it was shown that various lifestyle selections led to increased match likelihood among Veggie Mingle users.

As a result, it might be wise to allow users to select, either hidden or publicly, values that they are “seeking.” These would not be mere filters, but rather would highlight shared values or lifestyle badges/identifiers on user profiles. It may also result in the algorithm which suggests user profiles to users pushing some profiles over others. These curated profiles would likely see higher positive match likelihoods, as we can see from the exploratory data analysis.

These changes, if successful, would lead to more matches. More matches would lead to higher user engagement, and therefore greater user satisfaction. This in turn would boost statistics for user success metrics, which could be leveraged for marketing and advertising.

3.) Allow for Greater Choice

Some features, such as travel preferences, favorite activity, and music taste, allow for a single selection. They also only contain a list of predetermined levels, usually three or four different categories. In reality, users are likely more diverse than these categories. Allowing for more choices would allow users to be more specific, and in turn, see more specifically what they want in dating partners.

The conclusions that the exploratory data analysis and ML modeling lead to repeatedly show that overlapping interests present higher likelihoods for positive match outcomes. Allowing users more choice in how they present themselves to other users allows for narrower overlap between other users with those specific tastes– and therefore much better match likelihoods in those groups.

The upsides here are the same as before, higher engagement, greater user satisfaction, and a better bottom line for Veggie Mingle.

5. Conclusion

This project sought to identify the key factors driving successful matches on Veggie Mingle and to provide actionable insights for improving the platform’s performance.The initial hypothesis proposed by the exploratory data analysis was that there is a relationship between self-identified lifestyle preferences and match likelihood. This held true.

The analysis revealed that higher online activity and shared lifestyle traits are associated with increased match likelihood, while some lifestyle preferences, such as favorite music, have notable impacts on match outcomes.

However, the skewed data set and small effect sizes posed challenges for predictive modeling, resulting in models with limited discriminatory power. Despite these limitations, the findings underscore the importance of user engagement, profile completeness, and shared values in increasing match likelihood.

In addition, the variable importance plots in the most successful machine learning model, a random forest model, suggests that the most important predictors of match success are not lifestyle profile selections— but rather variables concerning app engagement. These were variables such as online activity, account duration, and account completeness.

The recommendations outlined—such as incentives to complete profiles, highlighting shared traits, and expanding user options—are designed to address these findings. While the current analysis is a strong starting point, future work should focus on gathering additional data, refining feature engineering, and testing the impact of suggested changes on user outcomes.

By implementing these strategies, Veggie Mingle can enhance user satisfaction, improve match rates, and strengthen its position as the go-to dating platform for users with plant-based diets. .

6.2 Machine Learning Models

We split the data, but, because there are two outcome variables, we have to remove the categorical variable from the Linear Regression model. This means we’ll need to do this splitting a second time, with cross validation included, for the classification models.

set.seed(1443385)

# Split it.
MingleSplit <- VeggieData |>
  initial_split(prop = 0.75, strata = matched)

# Training
MingleTraining <- MingleSplit |>
  training()

# Testing
MingleTesting <- MingleSplit |> 
  testing()

Minglefolds <- vfold_cv(VeggieData, v = 5)

We need to create two different recipes, one for regression models and another for classification models.

# Need two recipes, one for the linear regression model with "Total Matches"
RegressionRecipe <- recipe(total_matches ~ ., data = MingleTraining) |>
                   step_rm(matched, user_id) |> # Identifier variable may lead to overfitting, and is irrelevant to predictions. 
                   step_YeoJohnson(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes()) |> 
                   step_normalize(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes()) |> 
                   step_dummy(all_nominal(), - all_outcomes())

# And one for classification models with "Matched."
ClassificationRecipe <- recipe(matched ~ ., data = MingleTraining) |>
                   step_rm(total_matches, user_id) |> # Identifier variable may lead to overfitting, and is irrelevant to predictions. 
                   step_YeoJohnson(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes()) |> 
                   step_normalize(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes()) |> 
                   step_dummy(all_nominal(), - all_outcomes())

Check to see if the transformations worked as intended

# Regression Transformations
Regression_Training_Baked <- RegressionRecipe |> 
  prep() |> 
  bake(new_data = MingleTraining)

# View results
Regression_Training_Baked

# Classification Transformations
Classification_Training_Baked <- ClassificationRecipe |> 
  prep() |> 
  bake(new_data = MingleTraining)

# View results
Classification_Training_Baked

Random Forest

Create Model

Mingle_Forest <-  rand_forest(mtry = tune(),
                              trees = tune(),
                              min_n = tune()) |> 
  set_engine('ranger', importance = "impurity") |> 
  set_mode('classification')

Add a workflow to it

Forest_WF<- workflow() |> 
  add_model(Mingle_Forest) |> 
  add_recipe(ClassificationRecipe)

Hyperparameter Tuning with tune_grid()

set.seed(1443385)

# Create a random grid for tuning
rf_grid <- grid_random(mtry() |> 
                         range_set(c(5, 30)), # Dataframe has 35 columns, chopped five off either end to get a range mostly in the middle and away from the ends
                       trees(),
                       min_n(),
                       size = 10)

# Tuning Hyperparamters using resampling 
rf_tuning <- Forest_WF |> 
             tune_grid(resamples = Minglefolds,
                       grid = rf_grid)

# show the top 5 best models based on ROCAUC
rf_tuning |> 
  show_best(metric = 'roc_auc')
